\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Inference for measures of agreement with multiple raters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Jonas Moss 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
orcid{0000-0002-6876-6964}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Department of Data Science and Analytics
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

BI Norwegian Business School
\emph on

\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

jonas.moss@bi.no
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Most measures of agreement are chance-corrected measures of agreement.
 They differ in three dimensions: their definition of chance agreement,
 their choice of disagreement function, and how they handle multiple raters.
 Chance agreement is usually defined following either Cohen's kappa or Fleiss'
 kappa.
 The disagreement function is usually either the nominal, quadratic, or
 the absolute value function.
 But how to handle multiple raters is contentious, with the main contenders
 being Fleiss' kappa, Conger's kappa, and Hubert's kappa, the variant of
 Fleiss' kappa where agreement is only said to occur if every rater agrees.
 More generally, multi-rater agreement coefficients can be defined in a
 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-wise way, where the disagreement weighting function uses 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 of the raters.
 This paper contains two main contributions.
 (a) We propose to use Fréchet variances to handle multiple raters.
 The Fréchet variances are intuitive disagreement measures, and turn out
 to generalize the nominal, quadratic, and absolute value functions to the
 case of more than 2 raters.
 (b) We derive the limit theory of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-wise weighted agreement coefficients, with chance agreement either of the
 Cohen type or Fleiss type, for the case when every item is rated by the
 same number of raters.
 Trying out three confidence interval constructions, we end up recommending
 to calculate confidence intervals using the arcsine transform or the Fisher
 transform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most popular measures of inter-rater agreement involve correction for chance
 agreement.
 These can be written on the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{p_{a}-p_{ca}}{1-p_{ca}}=1-\frac{p_{d}}{p_{cd}},\label{eq:chance-corrected measure of agrement}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $p_{d}$
\end_inset

) is the percent agreement (disagreement) between the raters and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ca}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $p_{cd}$
\end_inset

) is the chance agreement (disagreement) between the raters.
 Such measures are frequently called 
\emph on
chance-corrected measures of agreement
\emph default
.
 Well-known examples of coefficients in this class are Cohen's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Cohen1960-mp"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 kappa and its weighted variant 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Cohen1968-sb"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Krippendorff's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Krippendorff1970-gl"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 alpha, Scott's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Scott1955-vn"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 pi, and Fleiss' 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Fleiss1971-to"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 kappa.
 Some of these coefficients are either defined only for two raters.
 The rest are defined in a pairwise manner, in the sense that they measure
 agreement between two raters at a time.
 But not every proposed measure of agreement is defined on pairs of raters.
 The most famous is Hubert's kappa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Hubert1977-ox"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which was recently studied in detail by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Martin_Andres2020-jr"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Other two-rater agreement coefficients include Conger's kappa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Conger1980-yx,Light1971-ad"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which is Cohen's kappa generalized to multiple raters, the 
\begin_inset Formula $AC_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and the recent coefficient of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Van_Oest2019-pm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no consensus about how multi-rater agreement coefficients should
 be defined.
 Broadly speaking, there are two options, pairwise coefficients and consensus
 coefficients.
 Pairwise coefficients measure agreement between pairs of raters 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Conger1980-yx"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, while consensus coefficients measure the simultaneous agreement between
 all raters.
 In particular, consensus coefficients support the notion that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

agreement occurs if and only if all raters agree on the categorization of
 an object
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hubert1977-ox"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Both pairwise and consensus-based definitions of agreement are variants
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-wise measures of agreement 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Conger1980-yx"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, where agreement is measured among 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-tuples of raters.
 But not-trivial ways to measure agreement is hard to come by when 
\begin_inset Formula $2<g<R$
\end_inset

.
 In Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Fréchet-variances"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we introduce a framework for handling 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-wise measures on agreement based on the concept of 
\emph on
Fréchet variances 
\emph default

\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dubey2019-rh"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The Fréchet variances, based on the Fréchet mean, generalize the variance,
 and the measures of agreement based on them generalize the nominal, linearly
 weighted, and quadratically weighted pairwise measures of agreement in
 a natural way.
 They are easily interpretable as, you measure how much do the raters disagree
 with the (generalized) mean rater, and then adjust for chance.
 For nominal data in particular, they measure how many raters disagree with
 the modal rater, with a resulting agreement measure less extreme than Hubert's
 kappa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hubert1977-ox"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming multivariate normality of the judgments, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Section 3"
key "Lin1989-kf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 derived the asymptotic distribution of Cohen's kappa with quadratic weights.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Fleiss1971-to"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 introduced a formula for the standard error of Fleiss' kappa, but later
 showed that it was incorrect.
 Using the properties of the multinomial distribution and the delta method,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Schouten1982-ou"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 found the asymptotic variance of the weighted Fleiss' kappa in the case
 when the number of categories is finite.
 Almost forty years later, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gwet2021-ht"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 found a consistent estimator of the variance for the unweighted Fleiss'
 kappa.
 We extend these results to the weighted 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-wise Fleiss' kappa for any number of categories below.
 In addition, we mention that bootstrap inference for Fleiss' kappa and
 Krippendorff's alpha was studied by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Zapf2016-eu"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin the paper by providing the definitions of two kinds of chance-corrected
 agreement coefficients, then we establish connections between a multi-rater
 weighted Cohen's kappa, the weighted Fleiss' kappa, Conger's kappa, Krippendorf
f's alpha, and Hubert's kappa (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Pairwise-kappa-like-statistics"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 We restrict ourselves to the simple context when every rater rates every
 item.
 In Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Fréchet-variances"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we introduce the Fréchet variances, a useful class of disagreement functions
 that make sense when 
\begin_inset Formula $2<g<R$
\end_inset

.
 Then we spell out the basic limit theory for this class of agreement coefficien
ts (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Estimation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), extending the results of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Schouten1980-iv"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Schouten1982-ou"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "OConnell1984-dz"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to vector-valued items and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-wise coefficients.
 We do this using 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lee2019-xm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, but there are other ways to arrive at the same results.
 Then we provide practical recommendations regarding the choice of confidence
 interval construction, obtained by comparing three confidence interval
 constructions: basic, arcsine transformed, and Fisher transformed.
 Using a simulation study (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Simulation-of-confidence-k2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), we find that the arcsine and Fisher intervals outperform the basic interval
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is small.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Measures of agreement
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Pairwise-kappa-like-statistics"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Discussing measures of inter-rater agreement requires quite a few definitions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{1},\ldots,x_{g})$
\end_inset

 be a
\emph on
 disagreement function
\emph default
, a positive and symmetric function of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 arguments that equals 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 when all 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

s are equal, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,\ldots,x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 This function measures the disagreement between the judgments 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\ldots,x_{k}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is understood as complete agreement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All disagreement functions in widespread use take two arguments.
 While there are infinitely many disagreement functions, the best known
 belong to the class of 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{p}$
\end_inset

 quasi-norms, 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0,1,2$
\end_inset

, potentially raised to the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th power.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{p}$
\end_inset

 quasi-norms, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{g}$
\end_inset

 are defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\|x\|_{p}=(\sum_{i=1}^{g}|x_{i}|^{p})^{1/p}.\label{eq:d_p_definitio}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $||x||_{0}=\sum_{i=1}^{g}1[x_{i}\neq0]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $||x||_{\infty}=(\sum_{i=1}^{g}|x_{i}|^{p})^{1/p}$
\end_inset

, as can be verified by taking the limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $||x||_{p}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $p\to0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\to\infty$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 It is well known that 
\begin_inset Formula $||x||_{p}$
\end_inset

 are proper norms if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq1$
\end_inset

, as the triangle inequality is violated when 
\begin_inset Formula $1>p\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the disagreement functions 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{p}$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{p}$
\end_inset

-norm evaluated in 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}-x_{2}$
\end_inset

, i.e.,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d_{p}(x_{1},x_{2})=||x_{1}-x_{2}||_{p}.\label{eq:d_p}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the case of scalar values, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}(x_{1},x_{2})=1[x_{1}\neq x_{2}]$
\end_inset

 is known as the 
\emph on
nominal disagreement function
\emph default
.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{p}$
\end_inset

-norm equals 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}(x_{1},x_{2})=|x_{1}-x_{2}|$
\end_inset

, which is known as the 
\emph on
absolute value disagreement function
\emph default
 (and sometimes the linear disagreement function).
 The 
\emph on
quadratic disagreement function
\emph default
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}^{2}(x_{1},x_{2})=(x_{1}-x_{2})^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Vector-valued variants of 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{p}^{p}$
\end_inset

 are far less common, but have been used by e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Berry2008-ga"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 isn't equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, we are mostly interested in the case when its arty equals the number of
 raters 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, the disagreement functions often measure the degree of consensus
 among the raters, with 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 reflecting complete consensus.
 The most obvious choice is the Hubert disagreement function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d(x_{1},\ldots,x_{K})=1-1[x_{1}=\cdots=x_{K}]\label{eq:Hubertweight}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which equals 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 if and only if every rater agrees on a rating.
 It is the disagreement function employed in Hubert's kappa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hubert1977-ox"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This is not the only reasonable disagreement function for multiple raters,
 however.
 We will come back to that in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Fréchet-variances"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We present our results in terms of disagreement functions instead of the
 more popular agreement functions (i.e., positive functions bounded by 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 signifies maximal agreement, sometimes with the additional assumption that
 
\begin_inset Formula $a\geq0$
\end_inset

).
 We do this mainly for mathematical convenience.
 Agreement functions and disagreement functions are tightly related, for
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is an agreement function then 
\begin_inset Formula $d=1-a$
\end_inset

 is a disagreement function.
 See the appendix, p.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "subsec:Agreement-vs-disagreement"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for a more detailed discussion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 denote the number of raters and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 denote the numbers of items rated.
 We make several assumptions.
 First, we assume that the ratings are conditionally independent given the
 item.
 Second, we assume that every item is rated by exactly the same number of
 raters, which we refer to as the 
\emph on
rectangular design
\emph default
, which is common in the literature.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For instance, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Fleiss1971-to"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, in his paper introducing Fleiss' kappa, removed several ratings from this
 data to make sure the total number of ratings was 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 for each item.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The rectangular design assumption can be relaxed, but it is needed for
 the limit results.
 We sketch how to loosen it up in the appendix (p.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "subsec:Expanding-the-definitions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Third, we will assume either: (a) Fixed raters, so the same set of raters
 rate every item, most commonly associated with applications of Cohen's
 kappa, or (b) Exchangeable ratings given the item, which is the case when
 the ratings are independent and identically distributed conditional on
 the item rater, an implicit assumption underlying most applications of
 Fleiss' kappa, e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Fleiss1971-to"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In case (b), the marginal distributions for all raters will be equal, which
 implies that the population value of the Fleiss' kappa equals the population
 value of the generalized Cohen's kappa, both defined below.
 But the sample Fleiss' kappa is the preferred sample estimator, as it is
 invariant under changes of the raters' identities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will also assume that the ratings are made independently of one another
 in the sense the ratings on the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th item in no way affects the ratings on 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th item.
 This situation corresponds to a statistical model where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}_{1},\boldsymbol{X}_{2},...,\boldsymbol{X}_{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-dimensional vectors (whose elements may also be vectors) are sampled independen
tly from some distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Be aware that we 
\emph on
do not
\emph default
 assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}_{k}$
\end_inset

 contains only categorical values, or a finite number of values; the elements
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}_{k}$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary in our framework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our intention is to collect the kappas of Cohen, Fleiss, Conger, Hubert,
 and so on, into a coherent framework of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-wise agreement coefficients.
 To do this we will have to define some quantities.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{i}=(x_{i1},x_{i2},\ldots,x_{iR})$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-dimensional vector of observed ratings and recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is the dimension of our disagreement function 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
The disagreement 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{1}$
\end_inset

,
\series default
 as measured by 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 The purpose of this quantity is to translate an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-dimensional disagreement function 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 into a disagreement function taking an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-dimensional vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{i}$
\end_inset

 as input.
 It is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{1})=\binom{R}{g}^{-1}\sum_{j_{i}}d(\boldsymbol{x}_{1j_{1}},\ldots,\boldsymbol{x}_{1j_{g}}),\label{eq:D_d}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the sum runs over all 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-dimensional subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,\ldots,R\}$
\end_inset

 with order ignored, i.e., the 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-combinations of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 The expression is simplified when 
\begin_inset Formula $g=R$
\end_inset

, as 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{1})=d(\boldsymbol{x}_{11},\ldots,\boldsymbol{x}_{1R})$
\end_inset

 in this case.
 To gain some intuition about this quantity, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $g=2$
\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2}$
\end_inset

 are scalars, and consider the nominal disagreement function 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}(x_{1},x_{2})=1[x_{1}\neq x_{2}]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{1})=2R^{-1}(R-1)^{-1}\sum_{j_{1}>j_{2}}1[x_{1j_{1}}\neq x_{1j_{2}}]$
\end_inset

 is the percentage of times two raters precisely agree on their rating.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
The Cohen-type chance disagreement
\series default
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{1},...,\boldsymbol{x}_{g}$
\end_inset

, so called to differentiate it from the Fleiss-type chance disagreement.
 It is similar to the disagreement at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{1}$
\end_inset

, but this time the raters do not necessarily rate the same item, as one
 rater rates the first item (from 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{1}$
\end_inset

) another rater rates the second item (from 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{2}$
\end_inset

), and so on.
 We do not allow a rater to rate the same item more than once in a pass:
 Hence we need to choose 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 raters from a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 raters, and the chance disagreement is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{1},...,\boldsymbol{x}_{g})=\binom{R}{g}^{-1}\sum_{j_{i}}d(\boldsymbol{x}_{1j_{1}},\ldots,\boldsymbol{x}_{gj_{g}}),\label{eq:C_d}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the sum runs over all 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-dimensional subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,\ldots,R\}$
\end_inset

, i.e., the 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-combinations of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{d}(\boldsymbol{x})=C_{d}(\boldsymbol{x},,\ldots,\boldsymbol{x})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be symmetric, the expression is massively simplified to 
\begin_inset Formula $d(\boldsymbol{x}_{1j_{1}},\ldots,\boldsymbol{x}_{Rj_{R}})$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $g=R$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $g=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{1},\boldsymbol{x}_{2})=R^{-1}(R-1)^{-1}\sum_{j_{1}\neq j_{2}}d(\boldsymbol{x}_{1j_{1}},\boldsymbol{x}_{2j_{2}})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
The Fleiss-type chance disagreement
\series default
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{1},...,\boldsymbol{x}_{g}$
\end_inset

 is similar, but allows the same rater (or rater index) to rate an item
 multiple times.
 Its definition is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{1},...,\boldsymbol{x}_{g})=R^{-g}\sum_{j_{i}}d(\boldsymbol{x}_{1j_{1}},\ldots,\boldsymbol{x}_{gj_{g}}),
\]

\end_inset

where the sum runs over the product set 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{g}$
\end_inset

.
 The expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{w}(\boldsymbol{x}_{1},...,\boldsymbol{x}_{g})$
\end_inset

 is not dramatically simplified when 
\begin_inset Formula $g=R$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $g=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{1},\boldsymbol{x}_{2})=R^{-2}\sum_{j_{1},j_{2}}d(\boldsymbol{x}_{1j_{1}},\boldsymbol{x}_{2j_{2}})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will call the expected values of these quantities the 
\emph on
mean disagreement
\emph default
, the 
\emph on
mean Cohen-type chance disagreement
\emph default
, and the 
\emph on
mean Fleiss-type chance disagreement
\emph default
.
 Slightly abusing notation, we denote them as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{d}=E[D_{d}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1})],\quad C_{d}=E[C_{d}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1},\ldots,\boldsymbol{X}_{g})],\quad F_{d}=E[F_{d}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1},\ldots,\boldsymbol{X}_{g})],\label{eq:p_wa-p_wc-p_wf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}_{1},\ldots,\boldsymbol{X}_{g}$
\end_inset

 are independently sampled from the same distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Discussions about the difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $E[C_{d}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1},\ldots,\boldsymbol{X}_{g})]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E[F_{d}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1},\ldots,\boldsymbol{X}_{g})]$
\end_inset

, and why to prefer one over the other, are abundant in the literature,
 often in the context of the so-called paradox of kappa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cicchetti1990-dj"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim F$
\end_inset

 be a vector of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 ratings and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 be an agreement function with dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Define the population values of the generalized Cohen's kappa 
\begin_inset Formula $(\kappa_{d})$
\end_inset

 and Fleiss' kappa 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pi_{d})$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\kappa_{d}=1-\frac{D_{d}}{C_{d}},\quad\pi_{d}=1-\frac{D_{d}}{F_{d}}.\label{eq:kappa and pi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have decided to denote Fleiss' kappa as 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{d}$
\end_inset

 as it's strictly speaking a generalization of Scott's pi 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Scott1955-vn"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, not Cohen's kappa.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $g=2$
\end_inset

, the kappas are commonly known as pairwise agreement coefficients.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $2\leq g\leq R$
\end_inset

, they are called 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-wise agreement coefficients, and when 
\begin_inset Formula $g=R$
\end_inset

, they are sometimes called consensus coefficients.
 The case when 
\begin_inset Formula $2<g<R$
\end_inset

 has received little attention in the literature, with some exceptions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Warrens2012-pc"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The definition of the weighted Fleiss' kappa is a straight-forward generalizatio
n of Fleiss' kappa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Fleiss1971-to"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to hold for any disagreement function of any dimension, not just 
\begin_inset Formula $g=2$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $g=R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is the nominal disagreement, it equals Hubert's kappa.
 Likewise, the definition of the weighted Conger's kappa is an extension
 of Conger's kappa to the weighted case with 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq2$
\end_inset

 allowed.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $g=R$
\end_inset

, it equals the Schuster–Smith coefficient 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "eq. 1"
key "Schuster2005-fa"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Schuster–Smith coefficient, a generalized Cohen's kappa, encompasses
 the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $2<g<R$
\end_inset

 provided their weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $v(s)$
\end_inset

 is appropriately defined, see the discussion on dispersion weights in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Schuster2005-fa"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Berry1988-nc"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 discussed 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{d}$
\end_inset

 for
