\begin_layout Section
Fréchet variances for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-wise agreement coefficients
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Fréchet-variances"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most popular measures of agreement are defined only in a pairwise manner
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g=2$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to find reasonable disagreement measures in this case, as one
 can draw on the literature on norms and distances.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{p}$
\end_inset

 distances are the obvious choices, but there are many other options, such
 as the Huber loss 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Huber1964-fm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or LINEX loss 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Varian1975-cd"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the setting of Hubert's kappa and the Schuster–Smith coefficient we have
 
\begin_inset Formula $g=R$
\end_inset

, and it is suddenly not that easy to find reasonable disagreement functions
 anymore.
 The disagreement weight used in Hubert's kappa, 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{1},\ldots,x_{R})=1-1[x_{1}=\cdots=x_{R}]$
\end_inset

, will penalize any number of discordant ratings equally, yielding the often
 undesirable outcome that most sets of ratings will be in complete disagreement.
 But there are less sensitive way to count nominal disagreements.
 Consider the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

 raters using categories 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $7$
\end_inset

 giving rating 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 giving rating 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 giving rating 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 Then Hubert's disagreement rating is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, as there are raters who disagree at all, and the pairwise (nominal) disagreeme
nt is 
\begin_inset Formula $46/100$
\end_inset

.
 But it sounds reasonable to pick the modal rating (in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

), then report the number of ratings that disagree, in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

, divided by the number of raters.
 This 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

modal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 disagreement equals 
\begin_inset Formula $3/10$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes we wish to report the aggregate judgment from a set of raters.
 For instance, the median judgment of an item could be used as input to
 a regression model.
 In this case it's natural to measure how much more we get to know about
 the median of an item by asking our raters, compared to the situation when
 ask no one.
 Consider the case above again.
 If we replace the abstract category 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

, the data becomes ordinal, and we can use the median.
 The aggregate judgment would be the median judgment, which equals 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 It is well-known that the median of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\argmin_{\mu}\sum|x_{i}-\mu|$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\min\sum|x_{i}-\mu|$
\end_inset

 appears to be a reasonable measure of mean disagreement when we use the
 median as aggregation method.
 Observe that, for this data, 
\begin_inset Formula $\min\sum|x_{i}-\mu|=\min\sum|x_{i}-1|=4$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

modal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 disagreement and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

median
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 disagreement are instances of an intuitive generalization of the variance
 called the (generalized) Fréchet variance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dubey2019-rh"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The Fréchet mean 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Frechet1948-jo"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is a generalization of centroids to arbitrary distance functions 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset


\emph on

\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Fréchet mean and variances is usually defined slightly differently,
 using 
\begin_inset Formula $l^{2}(x,x_{k})$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,x_{k})$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 being a metric.
 Our definition of the Fréchet mean is sometimes called the generalized
 Fréchet mean or the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

-Fréchet mean.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph default
; likewise, the Fréchet variance is a generalization of dispersion to any
 such distance function.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 be a distance function satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)\ge0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,x)=0$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{x_{1},x_{2},\ldots,x_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be a set of points.
 The sample 
\emph on
Fréchet mean
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is defined as the (not necessarily unique) point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{l}$
\end_inset

 that minimizes the sum of distances to all points in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{l}=\argmin_{\mu}\sum_{k=1}^{n}l(\mu,x_{k}).\label{eq:generalized-frechet-mean}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, the sample 
\emph on
Fréchet variance
\emph default
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with loss function 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V(l)=\min_{\mu}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{1}{n}l(\mu,x_{i})=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{1}{n}l(\mu_{l},x_{i}).\label{eq:generalized-frechet-variance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The Fréchet mean and Fréchet variance are best understood through a decision-the
oretic lens: The Fréchet mean of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 represents your best judgment of an item's true classification or value
 according to the loss 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

; the Fréchet variance 
\begin_inset Formula $V(l)$
\end_inset

 is the decision-theoretic risk associated with the choice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-dimensional disagreement based on 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d(\boldsymbol{x}_{1},\ldots,\boldsymbol{x}_{g})=V(l)[\boldsymbol{x}_{1},\ldots,\boldsymbol{x}_{g}].\label{eq:disagreement-frechet}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now we may use the definitions of Cohen's kappa and Fleiss' kappa to calculate
 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{d'}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{d'}$
\end_inset

.The disagreement measure is easy to understand and visualize, and corresponds
 to our intuitive understanding of disagreement quite well.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will consider the following distances:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}(x,y)=1[x\neq y]$
\end_inset

.

\series default
 Generalizes the nominal distance.
 If the data is categorical, the generalized Fréchet mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{d}$
\end_inset

 equals the mode, and the generalized Fréchet variance equals the percentage
 of observations different from the mode.
 If we are dealing with vector-valued data with 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 elements each, it might be preferable to use 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{I}1[x_{i}\neq y_{i}]$
\end_inset

 instead, as it counts each dimension of the nominal data separately.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}(x,y)=||x-y||_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The generalized Fréchet mean equals the coordinate-wise sample median.
 The generalized Fréchet variance equals the coordinate sum of sample mean
 absolute deviation from the median, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{i}\frac{1}{R}\sum_{k=1}^{R}|x_{ri}-\mu_{i}|$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the coordinate wise medians.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}^{2}(x,y)=||x-y||_{2}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The generalized Fréchet mean equals the coordinate wise sample mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{d}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}$
\end_inset

, and the Fréchet variance equals the biased sample variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{1},x_{2},\ldots,x_{n}\}$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{d}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_{i}-\mu_{d})^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}(x,y)=||x-y||_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The generalized Fréchet mean has no simple formula, but is known as the
 
\emph on
geometric median
\emph default
.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 are scalars, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}=d_{1}$
\end_inset

, which implies that the Fréchet mean equals the median, hence the name.
 There is an extensive literature about the geometric median, see e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Drezner2002-oe"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for an overview and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Cohen2016-yv"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for how to compute it.
 Be aware that the geometric median is computationally more intensive than
 the generalized Fréchet mean based on 
\begin_inset Formula $||x-y||_{2}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 and pair of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2}$
\end_inset

, it holds that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V(d_{p})[x_{1},x_{2}]=\frac{1}{2}d_{p}(x_{1},x_{2}),\quad V(d_{p}^{p})[x_{1},x_{2}]=\frac{1}{2^{p}}d_{p}^{p}(x_{1},x_{2}).\label{eq:Vdp=dp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{d_{p}}=\kappa_{V(d_{p})}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{d_{p}^{p}}=\kappa_{V(d_{p}^{p})}$
\end_inset

 when we are dealing with pairwise agreement.
 Thus the Fréchet variances generalize the pairwise agreement for these
 distances (proved in the appendix, page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "subsec:Proof-of-equivalence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "exa:example"

\end_inset

Suppose you have 
\begin_inset Formula $R=5$
\end_inset

 raters who rate 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 items, yielding ratings 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,1,2,1,1)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,2,3,2,2)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,1,1,1,1)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,3,4,4,5)$
\end_inset

.
 The Fréchet means using the loss 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)=d_{1}(x,y)=|x-y|$
\end_inset

 equals the coordinate-wise sample medians 
\begin_inset Formula $1,2,1,4$
\end_inset

.
 The Fréchet variances are 
\begin_inset Formula $V(d_{1})=(0.2,0.4,0.2,0.8)$
\end_inset

.
 To calculate the sample Cohen's kappa with 
\begin_inset Formula $d=V(d_{1})$
\end_inset

 we first find the mean disagreement 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:d_hat"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{V(d_{1})}=0.4$
\end_inset

, then the mean Cohen disagreement 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:pwc_hat"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, which is 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx0.73$
\end_inset

.
 Thus Cohen's kappa is 
\begin_inset Formula $1-0.4/0.73=0.45$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We believe the most useful distance measures will typically be 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}$
\end_inset

 would be used when there is no known ordinal structure in the data, and
 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}$
\end_inset

 would be used if there is a known ordinal structure.
 The quadratic distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}^{2}$
\end_inset

 could be used as well, but is harder to justify, as it's usually not obvious
 why we would be interested in the squared distance between two observations
 rather than just the distance itself.
 The distances 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{p},p\in(1,\infty]$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}$
\end_inset

 included, are even harder to recommend, as they do not work in a coordinate-wis
e manner.
 In any case, it seems most reasonable to go with the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-wise variants of these distance measures, as they make use of all the available
 information, but 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-wise agreement coefficients (
\begin_inset Formula $g<R)$
\end_inset

 do not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main reason to use Fréchet variances is its simple and practical interpretat
ion.
 Consider the case of nominal ratings with 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 raters.
 You might have to supply a final aggregated rating from all of your ratings,
 and then it is very natural to use the mode.
 The Fréchet variance using 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}$
\end_inset

 tells you how much better your aggregate prediction based on the mode will
 be, compared to using just the marginal distribution of the ratings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Fleiss1971-to"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset

In the paper introducing what is now called Fleiss' kappa, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Fleiss1971-to"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 discussed an example involving 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 different kinds of diagnoses, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=30$
\end_inset

 patients, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R=6$
\end_inset

 psychiatrists.
 The data is originally from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Sandifer1968-hz"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, but Fleiss removed some ratings to make the design rectangular.
 The raters are not the same for all raters, but it appears plausible to
 assume that ratings are exchangeable given the item.
 The diagnoses are essentially categorical in nature, hence we will only
 consider 
\begin_inset Formula $V(d_{0})$
\end_inset

 and Hubert's disagreement function.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $g=R=6$
\end_inset

, the difference between Hubert's kappa 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pi=0.166)$
\end_inset

 and Fleiss' kappa using the 
\begin_inset Formula $V(d_{0})$
\end_inset

 distance 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pi=0.486)$
\end_inset

 is substantial, which suggests that a sizeable number of rating vectors
 contain at least one rating that disagrees with the others.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:counts-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 summarizes the relevant aspects of the data.
 The maximal agreement row could potentially go from 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

, but on this data set, the smallest number raters agreeing on a classification
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 According to the Hubert distance the raters disagree quite a lot, as only
 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 items have a distance of 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and the rest a distance of 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $V(d_{0})$
\end_inset

 equals 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 minus the maximal agreement (i.e., the number of elements distinct from the
 mode), and results in much smaller chance-adjusted agreement.
\end_layout

