\begin_layout Section
Estimation and inference
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Estimation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sample estimates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}_{1},...,\boldsymbol{X}_{n}\sim F$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 iid vectors of ratings by 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 raters.
 Then there is a single natural sample estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{d}$
\end_inset

, namely 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{D}_{d}=n^{-1}\sum_{i}D_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i}).\label{eq:d_hat}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

There are, however, two natural estimators of the Cohen-type chance disagreement
, one them a 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

-statistic 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Chapter 4.2"
key "Lee2019-xm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the other a 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistic 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Chapter 1"
key "Lee2019-xm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{C}_{d} & = & n^{-g}\sum_{i_{k}}C_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i_{1}},...,\boldsymbol{x}_{i_{g}})\quad\textrm{and}\quad\hat{C}_{d}^{u}=\binom{n}{g}^{-1}\sum_{i_{k}}C_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i_{1}},...,\boldsymbol{x}_{i_{g}}),\label{eq:pwc_hat}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the first estimator counts every combination with repetitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1},i_{2},\ldots,i_{g}$
\end_inset

 and the second estimator counts the unordered combinations 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}<i_{2}<\ldots<i_{g}$
\end_inset

.
 Using the basic results of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Chapter 1"
key "Lee2019-xm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{d}^{u}$
\end_inset

 is the unique minimum variance unbiased estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{d}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, from a well-known correspondence between 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

-statistics, the asymptotic distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}_{d}$
\end_inset

 coincides with the asymptotic distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}_{d}^{u}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Chapter 4, Theorem 1"
key "Lee2019-xm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, so the choice of between 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}_{d}^{u}$
\end_inset

 barely matters when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is sufficiently large.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Likewise, there are two natural estimators of the Fleiss-type weighted chance
 agreement,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{F}_{d} & = & n^{-g}\sum_{i_{k}}F_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i_{1}},...,\boldsymbol{x}_{i_{g}})\quad\textrm{and}\quad\hat{F}_{d}^{u}=\binom{n}{g}^{-1}\sum_{i_{k}}F_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i_{1}},...,\boldsymbol{x}_{i_{g}}),\label{eq:pwf_hat}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the index sets are as described above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can define two sample variants of Cohen's kappa (Fleiss' kappa),
 depending on which one of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}_{d}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}_{d}$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}_{d}^{u}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}_{d}^{u}$
\end_inset

) we choose to use.
 These are 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{d}=1-\hat{D}_{d}/\hat{C}_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{d}^{u}=1-\hat{D}_{d}/\hat{C}_{d}^{u}$
\end_inset

 for Cohen's kappa and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{d}=1-\hat{D}_{d}/\hat{F}_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{d}^{u}=1-\hat{D}_{d}/\hat{F}_{d}^{u}$
\end_inset

 for Fleiss' kappa.
 The definition of the sample Cohen's kappa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cohen1968-sb"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 agrees with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{w}$
\end_inset

, not 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{w}^{u}$
\end_inset

.
 Likewise, the sample Fleiss' kappa – with nominal disagreement – has definition
 agreeing with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{w}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Fleiss1971-to"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{w}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{w}$
\end_inset

 are faster to compute when the data isn't continuous.
 Since the estimators are asymptotically equivalent in any case, we will
 stick to the 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

-statistics 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{w}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{w}$
\end_inset

 for estimation, but use the 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistic form when deriving limit distributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Limit theory using 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}_{1},...,\boldsymbol{X}_{n}$
\end_inset

 be independently and identically distributed and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x_{1},\ldots,x_{k})$
\end_inset

 be a symmetric function.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistic of order 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 with kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U_{n}=\binom{n}{k}^{-1}\sum_{i_{1},\ldots,i_{k}}\psi(\boldsymbol{X}_{i_{1}},\ldots,\boldsymbol{X}_{i_{k}}),\label{eq:U-statistic}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the sum extends of over all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-dimensional tuples satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i_{1}<i_{2}<\ldots\le n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The theory of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics was established by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hoeffding1992-gq"
literal "false"

\end_inset

; for an introduction, see e.g.
 Chapter 6.1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Lehmann2004-ke"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Chapter 5 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Serfling1980-zr"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, or the textbook of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Lee2019-xm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These references handle 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics where the 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

s are real-valued, but their results, including the simple results below,
 hold for vector-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

s as well 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Korolyuk2013-nr"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Fleiss-type (Cohen-type) weighted chance agreement is a 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistic with kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{d}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $C_{d})$
\end_inset

, of order 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 The disagreement is a 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistic with kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{d}$
\end_inset

, which has order 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 To find the asymptotic variance of the kappas, we will use formulas for
 the asymptotic covariance of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2n}$
\end_inset

 be two 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 observations with symmetric kernel functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Define
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sigma_{1}^{2} & = & \Var(E[\psi_{1}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1},\ldots,\boldsymbol{X}_{k_{1}})\mid\boldsymbol{X}_{1})]),\\
\sigma_{12}^{2} & = & \Cov(E[\psi_{1}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1},\ldots,\boldsymbol{X}_{k_{1}})\mid\boldsymbol{X}_{1})],E[\psi_{2}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1},\ldots,\boldsymbol{X}_{k_{2}})\mid\boldsymbol{X}_{1})]).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Then it holds that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\Cov(U_{1n},U_{2n})\to k_{1}k_{2}\sigma_{12}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\Var(U_{1n})\to k_{1}^{2}\sigma_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Theorem 2, p. 76)"
key "Lee2019-xm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It is also possible to calculate the exact covariances, which could potentially
 make the asymptotic variances for the kappas perform better.
 See the appendix p.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "subsec:Variance-of--statistics"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for the formula for the exact covariance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Theorem 2, p. 17)"
key "Lee2019-xm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:limit lemma"

\end_inset

Assume every rater rates every item exactly once.
 Define the parameter vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}=(D_{d},C_{d},F_{d})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{p}}=(\hat{D}_{d},\hat{C}_{d},\hat{F}_{d})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{n}(\hat{\boldsymbol{p}}-\boldsymbol{p})\stackrel{d}{\to}N(0,\Sigma)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is the covariance matrix with elements
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{6}
\sigma_{11} & = & \sigma_{D}^{2} & = & \Var D_{d}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}) & ,\quad & \sigma_{12} & = & \sigma_{CD} & = & g\Cov(\mu_{C}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}),D_{d}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1})),\\
\sigma_{22} & = & \sigma_{C}^{2} & = & g^{2}\Var\mu_{C}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}) & ,\quad & \sigma_{13} & = & \sigma_{FD} & = & g\Cov(\mu_{F}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}),D_{d}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1})),\\
\sigma_{33} & = & \sigma_{F}^{2} & = & g^{2}\Var\mu_{F}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}) & ,\quad & \sigma_{23} & = & \sigma_{CF} & = & g\Cov(\mu_{C}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}),\mu_{F}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1})).
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

Here the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{C}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1})$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{F}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1})$
\end_inset

 are defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{C}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1})=E[C_{d}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1},\ldots,\boldsymbol{X}_{g})\mid\boldsymbol{X}_{1}]\quad\mu_{F}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1})=E[F_{d}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1},\ldots,\boldsymbol{X}_{g})\mid\boldsymbol{X}_{1}].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The form of the covariance matrix follows from the remarks preceding the
 lemma.
 Asymptotic normality follows from a general theorem about asymptotic normality
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics, see e.g.
 Theorem 2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 76"
key "Lee2019-xm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to use Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:limit lemma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to find the limit distribution of the generalized Cohen's kappa and Fleiss'
 kappa.
 To this end, recall the multivariate delta method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Theorem 5.2.3"
before "see, e.g.,"
key "Lehmann2004-ke"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}^{k}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be continuously differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{n}(\hat{\theta}-\theta)\stackrel{d}{\to}N(0,\Sigma)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sqrt{n}[f(\hat{\theta})-f(\theta)]\stackrel{d}{\to}N(0,\nabla f(\theta)^{T}\Sigma\nabla f(\theta)),\label{eq:delta method}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla f(\theta)$
\end_inset

 denotes the gradient of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of Cohen's kappa and Fleiss' kappa, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\nabla\kappa_{d} & = & \frac{1}{C_{d}}\left(-1,\frac{D_{d}}{C_{d}}\right),\quad\nabla\pi_{d}=\frac{1}{F_{d}}\left(-1,\frac{D_{d}}{F_{d}}\right).\label{eq:derivative}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using some algebra, the expressions for the asymptotic variances follow
 from Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:limit lemma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and the gradients above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:The-asymptotic-variances"

\end_inset

Assume every rater rates every item exactly once.
 Then Cohen's kappa 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-wise Fleiss' kappa 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{d}$
\end_inset

 are asymptotically normal, and their asymptotic variances are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\sigma_{\kappa}^{2} & = & \sigma_{D}^{2}\frac{1}{C_{d}^{2}}-2\sigma_{CD}\frac{D_{d}}{C_{d}^{3}}+\sigma_{C}^{2}\frac{D_{d}^{2}}{C_{d}^{4}},\label{eq:cohen variance}\\
\sigma_{\pi}^{2} & = & \sigma_{D}^{2}\frac{1}{F_{d}^{2}}-2\sigma_{FD}\frac{D_{d}}{F_{d}^{3}}+\sigma_{F}^{2}\frac{D_{d}^{2}}{F_{d}^{4}}.\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

These results hold for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{d}^{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{d}^{u}$
\end_inset

 too.
 Since the sample Krippendorff's alpha equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}_{d}=\hat{\pi}_{d}+\frac{1}{2Rn}(1-\hat{\pi}_{d})$
\end_inset

, it is also asymptotically normal with asymptotic variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\pi}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With 
\begin_inset Formula $g=2$
\end_inset

 and a finite number of categories, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Schouten1980-iv"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 derived 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\pi}^{2}$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Schouten1982-ou"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "OConnell1984-dz"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 derived 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\kappa}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The result for Krippendorff's alpha is, to our knowledge, new.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
A brief aside on Krippendorff's alpha
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Krippendorff's alpha 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Krippendorff1970-gl"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is another popular agreement coefficient, especially popular in content
 analysis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Krippendorff2018-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It has no population definition, but its sample definition equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}_{d}=\hat{\pi}_{d}+\frac{1}{N}(1-\hat{\pi}_{d}),$
\end_inset

 (the total sample size 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 equals 
\begin_inset Formula $2Jn$
\end_inset

 in the case of a rectangular design) see Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:krippendorfff"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 in the appendix for a justification.
 For this reason, all of the results about the limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{w}^{u}$
\end_inset

 applies to Krippendorff's alpha as well, as it is an asymptotically equivalent
 estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{d}$
\end_inset

.
 Note, however, that Krippendorff 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Krippendorff2018-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 emphasizes the use of non-rectangular designs, and the limit results in
 the preceding section do not hold for such study designs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Estimating the variances
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Estimating-the-variances"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The unknown disagreement measures 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}_{d}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}_{d}$
\end_inset

 can be estimated using their sample counterparts.
 The variances and covariances can be estimated using the empirical (co)variance
s of the estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}$
\end_inset

s, defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{\mu}_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i}) & = & D_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i}),\label{eq:mu_hats}\\
\hat{\mu}_{dc}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i}) & = & n^{-(g-1)}\sum_{i_{j}}^{n}C_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i},\boldsymbol{x}_{i_{1}},\ldots,\boldsymbol{x}_{i_{k-1}}),\nonumber \\
\hat{\mu}_{df}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i}) & = & n^{-(g-1)}\sum_{i_{j}}^{n}F_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i},\boldsymbol{x}_{i_{1}},\ldots,\boldsymbol{x}_{i_{k-1}}).\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

From the definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}_{d},\hat{C}_{d}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}_{d},$
\end_inset

 (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Estimation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, p.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "sec:Estimation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), we quickly deduce that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\hat{\mu}_{d}}=\hat{D}_{d}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\hat{\mu}_{dc}}=\hat{C}_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $,\overline{\hat{\mu}_{fc}}=\hat{F}_{d}$
\end_inset

.
 Using this fact, we can define the estimators
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\sigma}_{C}^{2}=\frac{g^{2}}{n-1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}(\hat{\mu}_{dc}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i})-\hat{C}_{d})^{2},\quad\hat{\sigma}_{CD}=\frac{g}{n-1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}(\hat{\mu}_{dc}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i})-\hat{C}_{d})(\hat{\mu}_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i})-\hat{D}_{d}),
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{D}^{2}=\frac{1}{n-1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}(\hat{\mu}_{d}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i})-\hat{D}_{d})^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, we can estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{FD}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in the same way, substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}_{df}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}_{dc}$
\end_inset

.
 Using the formulas for the theoretical variances 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cohen variance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we find the estimators
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\sigma}_{\kappa}^{2}=\hat{\sigma}_{D}^{2}\frac{1}{\hat{C}_{d}^{2}}-2\hat{\sigma}_{CD}\frac{\hat{D}_{d}}{\hat{C}_{d}^{3}}+\hat{\sigma}_{C}^{2}\frac{\hat{D}_{d}^{2}}{\hat{C}_{d}^{4}},\label{eq:cohen variance formula}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\sigma}_{\pi}^{2}=\hat{\sigma}_{D}^{2}\frac{1}{\hat{F}_{d}^{2}}-2\hat{\sigma}_{FD}\frac{\hat{D}_{d}}{\hat{F}_{d}^{3}}+\hat{\sigma}_{F}^{2}\frac{\hat{D}_{d}^{2}}{\hat{F}_{d}^{4}}.\label{eq:fleiss variance formula}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variance estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{\pi}^{2}$
\end_inset

 coincides with that of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "equation 4"
key "Gwet2021-ht"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, in the case of nominal weights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Improving approximate normality with the arcsine and Fisher transforms 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is well-known that the 
\emph on
Fisher transform
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Fisher1915-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 improves inference for the correlation coefficient.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the sample correlation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\artanh(r)=\frac{1}{2}\log[(1+r)/(1-r)]$
\end_inset

 has approximately the same variance for most 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, and its distribution is closer to normal than that of the untransformed
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, especially when the population correlation is close to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 This transform makes sense outside the world of correlations; for instance,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Lin1989-kf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 used the Fisher transform to improve normality of the quadratically weighted
 Cohen's kappa.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The arcsine is another reasonable transformation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{d}$
\end_inset

.
 The arcsine is the inverse of the sine function from trigonometry, and
 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\arcsin x=\int1/\sqrt{1-x^{2}}dx$
\end_inset

.
 In ecology 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Warton2011-dk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the arcsine transformation denotes 
\begin_inset Formula $\arcsin\sqrt{p}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a probability.
 We do not take square root, however, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{d}$
\end_inset

 can be negative.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The arcsine is defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{d}\in[-1,1]$
\end_inset

, and the Fisher transform for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{d}\in(-1,1)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{d}<-1$
\end_inset

 is theoretically possible when 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 isn't quadratic.
 But, seeing as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{d}<-1$
\end_inset

 rarely happens, and that inference is of limited interest in such situations
 of extreme disagreement, we choose to ignore this problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "exa:Fisher transform"

\end_inset

 This example illustrates that the arcsine and Fisher transform may make
 the sampling distribution closer to the normal distribution.
 Let the number of raters be 
\begin_inset Formula $R=3$
\end_inset

, the disagreement function take 
\begin_inset Formula $g=2$
\end_inset

 arguments, and the number of items be 
\begin_inset Formula $n=20$
\end_inset

.
 The are five categories, and the true classification of an item is 
\begin_inset Formula $c=1,2,3,4,5$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/5$
\end_inset

 each.
 Every rater knows the true classification of an item with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $0.9$
\end_inset

.
 If they to do not know the correct classification, they will guess a classifica
tion from 
\begin_inset Formula $c=1,2,3,4,5$
\end_inset

 uniformly at random.
 We use quadratic weights.
 One can show that the population value of the quadratically weighted Cohen's
 kappa is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.816$
\end_inset

 under these circumstances, following the arguments of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Perreault1989-mg"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We simulate the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{d}$
\end_inset

 a total of 
\begin_inset Formula $N=50,000$
\end_inset

 times and transform them using the identity transform, the arcsine transform,
 and the Fisher transform.
 The results are in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Fisher transform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The arcsine transform makes appears to make the sampling distribution of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{w}$
\end_inset

 closest to the normal distribution, with the Fisher transform improving
 normality quite a bit as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
