name "fig:Fisher transform"

\end_inset

Simulated sampling distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{w}$
\end_inset

 for quadratic weights using three transformations, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=20$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R=3$
\end_inset

.
 The simulation setup is described in Example 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "exa:Fisher transform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The arcsine transform makes the sampling distribution closest to the normal
 distribution.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Calculating the limiting variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\arcsin\hat{\kappa}_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\arcsin\hat{\pi}_{d}$
\end_inset

 requires an additional application of the delta method.
 We use that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dx}\arcsin(x)=1/\sqrt{1-x^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dx}\artanh(x)=1/(1-x^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 The one-dimensional delta method states that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{n}(\hat{\theta}-\theta)\stackrel{d}{\to}N(0,\sigma^{2})$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{n}(f(\hat{\theta})-f(\theta))\stackrel{d}{\to}N(0,f'(\theta)^{2}\sigma^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\sqrt{n}(\arcsin\hat{\kappa}_{d}-\arcsin\kappa_{d}) & \to & N(0,(1-\kappa_{d}^{2})^{-1}\sigma_{\kappa}^{2}),\label{eq:arcsine limit}\\
\sqrt{n}(\artanh\hat{\kappa}_{d}-\artanh\kappa_{d}) & \to & N(0,(1-\kappa_{d}^{2})^{-2}\sigma_{\kappa}^{2}).\label{eq:artanh limit}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The expressions for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{d}$
\end_inset

 can be found by swapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{d}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\kappa}^{2}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\pi}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

