\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size scriptsize
\begin_inset Formula $^{*}$
\end_inset

The largest number of raters that agree on the classification of an item.
 Both 
\begin_inset Formula $V(d_{0})$
\end_inset

 and Hubert's distance depend only on this when 
\begin_inset Formula $g=R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

According to the Hubert distance the raters disagree a lot, as only 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 items have a distance of 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and the rest a distance of one.
 On th other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $V(d_{0})$
\end_inset

 equals 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 minus the maximal agreement (i.e., the number of elements distinct from the
 mode), and results in much smaller chance-adjusted agreement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Zapf2016-eu"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 studied bootstrap intervals for Fleiss' kappa and Krippendorff's alpha
 using simulations and a case study.
 Their case study concerned histopathological assessment of breast cancer,
 and involved ratings done by 
\begin_inset Formula $R=4$
\end_inset

 senior pathologists and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=50$
\end_inset

 breast cancer biopsies.
 We apply the arcsine method to calculate confidence intervals and point
 estimates (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Zapf"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 We focus on Cohen's kappa since the same four pathologists rate each cancer
 biopsy, but we include a column for Fleiss' kappa when 
\begin_inset Formula $g=4$
\end_inset

 for comparisons sake.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $g=4$
\end_inset

, Cohen's kappa and Fleiss' kappa are as good as indistinguishable.
 As can be verified using the code in the supplementary material, this happens
 for the other 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

s as well.
 It is not generally the case that Fleiss' kappa and Cohen's kappa nearly
 coincide, but is likely to happen if the marginal ratings are approximately
 the same for all raters, as is the case in this data set.
 There is a sizable difference between the disagreement functions, but there
 is not typically a big difference when changing 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

s, provided we keep the disagreement functions constant.
 It remains to be seen if this common or not.
 The exception is Hubert's disagreement function, which decreases by quite
 a bit.
 (As in the 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Fleiss1971-to"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 example, this is expected, as the Hubert's disagreement function is a consensus
 measure.) Observe that the quadratic Fréchet variance 
\begin_inset Formula $V(d_{2}^{2})$
\end_inset

 does not change with 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 at all.
 The estimators are not exactly the same for the Cohen type chance agreement,
 but one can show that the disagreement at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 equals with 
\begin_inset Formula $g=2+i$
\end_inset

 equals 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 times the disagreement when 
\begin_inset Formula $g=2$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that Fleiss' kappa is invariant under 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

