\begin_layout Section
Simulations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Simulation of confidence sets when 
\begin_inset Formula $g=2$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Simulation-of-confidence-k2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We include a small simulation study about the performance of confidence
 sets using two models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Number of raters
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 We use 
\begin_inset Formula $2,5,20$
\end_inset

, corresponding to a small, medium, and large selection of raters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Sample sizes
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 We use 
\begin_inset Formula $n=10,40,100$
\end_inset

, corresponding to small, medium-sized, and large agreement studies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Disagreement functions
\series default
.
 We use the classics: The nominal disagreement 
\begin_inset Formula $1[x\neq y]$
\end_inset

, quadratic disagreement 
\begin_inset Formula $(x-y)^{2}$
\end_inset

, and absolute value disagreement 
\begin_inset Formula $|x-y|$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Models.

\series default
 We simulate from two models.
 A Perreault–Leigh model for discrete ratings and a normal model for continuous
 ratings.
 These models are described in more detail below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Methods.

\series default
 We will use three methods for confidence interval construction: A basic
 interval without transformations, an arcsine-transformed interval, and
 a Fisher-transformed interval.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We describe our three confidence interval constructions only for Cohen's
 kappa, as the intervals using Fleiss' kappa can be found by replacing every
 instance 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{d}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{\kappa}^{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{\pi}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We use two-sided 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

-distribution-based confidence intervals with nominal level 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\alpha=0.95$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\alpha/2)$
\end_inset

-quantile of the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedem.
 The
\emph on
 
\emph default
basic interval is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[\hat{\kappa}_{d}-c\hat{\sigma}_{\kappa}/\sqrt{n-1},\hat{\kappa}_{d}+c\hat{\sigma}_{\kappa}/\sqrt{n-1}],\label{eq:basic CI}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}(\hat{\kappa}_{d})$
\end_inset

 is the estimated variance described in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cohen variance formula"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the arcsine interval replaces the basic limits with
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sin\left(\arcsin\hat{\kappa}_{d}\pm c(1-\hat{\kappa}_{d}^{2})^{-1/2}\hat{\sigma}_{\kappa}/\sqrt{n-1}\right),\label{eq:arcsine CI}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\hat{\kappa}_{d}^{2})^{-1}\hat{\sigma}_{\kappa}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the asymptotic variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\arcsin\hat{\kappa}_{d}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:arcsine limit"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The Fisher interval uses the area hyperbolic tangent,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tanh\left(\artanh\hat{\kappa}_{d}\pm c(1-\hat{\kappa}_{d}^{2})^{-1}\hat{\sigma}_{\kappa}/\sqrt{n-1}\right),\label{eq:artanh CI}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\hat{\kappa}_{d}^{2})^{-2}\hat{\sigma}_{\kappa}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the asymptotic variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\artanh\hat{\kappa}_{d}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:artanh limit"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
A Perreault–Leigh model
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:A-Perreault–Leigh-model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Perreault1989-mg"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 discussed a particular model for ratings where each rater either knows
 the correct answer or guesses uniformly at random.
 Similar models have been used by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gwet2008-qk,Maxwell1977-lf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, among others.
 We assume there are five categories encoded as 
\begin_inset Formula $C=(-2,-1,0,1,2)$
\end_inset

, and the distribution of the true classification distribution is uniform.
 For each item rated, the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th rater knows the correct classification with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{0.8}$
\end_inset

.
 If not, he guesses, picking a number from 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 uniformly at random.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{d}=\pi_{d}=0.8$
\end_inset

 for all weights and number of raters, as can be verified by following the
 arguments of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Perreault1989-mg"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We run each simulation 
\begin_inset Formula $N=10,000$
\end_inset

 times.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simulated lengths and coverages for Cohen's kappa are in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Cohen-guessing"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The table for Fleiss' kappa is similar, and can be found in the appendix,
 p.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "tab:Fleiss-guessing"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Two features stand out in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Cohen-guessing"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 First, the confidence intervals have almost indistinguishable lengths and
 coverages when either 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is large.
 Second, the basic interval has worse coverage than the arcsine and Fisher
 intervals when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is small, with the Fisher interval having slightly better coverage than
 the arcsine interval.
 However, the better coverage comes at the expense of greater lengths.
 In particular, for the absolute value weight, the coverage of the arcsine
 interval is greater than the coverage of the Fisher interval, but its length
 is shorter.
\end_layout

