\begin_layout Subsubsection
Normal model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this study, the rating data is distributed according to the multivariate
 normal 
\begin_inset Formula $N(0,\Sigma)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $R\times R$
\end_inset

 correlation matrix with off-diagonal elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{j_{1}j_{2}}=\rho$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}$
\end_inset

 denotes the absolute value disagreement and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}^{2}$
\end_inset

 the quadratic disagreement.
 The true values are 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{d_{2}}=\pi_{d_{2}^{2}}=\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{d_{1}}=\pi_{d_{1}}=1-\sqrt{1-\rho}$
\end_inset

.
 See the appendix (p.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "subsec:true values"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) for details on the computation of these true value.
 We use 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=0.7$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{d_{2}^{2}}=0.7$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{\textrm{d_{1}}}=0.45$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the nominal weight will not work for this continuous data, hence
 we simulate using only the quadratic and absolute value weights.
 We run each simulation 
\begin_inset Formula $N=1,000$
\end_inset

 times
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We use fewer simulations (
\begin_inset Formula $1,000$
\end_inset

) than in the previous simulation (
\begin_inset Formula $10,000$
\end_inset

) since estimation is far more computationally expensive when dealing with
 continuous data, as it does not allow for binning.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We note that agreement coefficients are frequently called concordance coefficie
nts when dealing with continuous data.
 Lin's concordance coefficient 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lin1989-kf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is a prominent example.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simulated lengths and coverages for Cohen's kappa are in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:cohen-normal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The table for Fleiss' kappa is similar, and can be found in the appendix
 (p.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "tab:Fleiss-normal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 From the table below, we see that there is barely any difference between
 the three confidence interval constructions.
 Taken together with the results for the Perreault–Leigh model, where the
 basic interval performs worse than the other two, we would recommend the
 usage of either the arcsine or Fisher interval.
\end_layout

