\begin_layout Section
Concluding remarks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When choosing an agreement coefficient one has to carefully think through
 exactly what one wishes to measure.
 The Fréchet variances are attractive due to their interpretation.
 You measure how much do the raters disagree with the (generalized) mean
 rater, and then adjust for chance.
 In the case of nominal data, we measure disagreement with the modal rater.
 When dealing with numerical data, we may measure disagreement with the
 median rater (using the absolute value distance), or the mean rater (using
 the quadratic distance), or use any other Fréchet variance defined on numeric
 data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When dealing with nominal data, we believe that using the Fréchet variance
 that measures the distance from the mode is a reasonable choice.
 But other options are certainly possible, even when dealing with 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-wise agreement measures.
 For instance, one could use the entropy instead, with distance measure
 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots,x_{g})=-\sum_{i=1}^{g}\frac{\#i}{g}\log\frac{\#i}{g},$
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\#i$
\end_inset

 counts the number of elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots,x_{g})$
\end_inset

 classified as 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The topic of how to choose reasonable distance measures for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-wise agreement studies has not been thoroughly studied, and there might
 be options preferable to the Fréchet variances that have not yet been found.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have only covered rectangular design, where every item is rated by the
 same number of raters.
 It is quite easy to generalize the definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{d}$
\end_inset

 to non-rectangular designs, as we have done in the appendix, p.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "subsec:Expanding-the-definitions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 But inference appears to be quite difficult, probably requiring additional
 assumptions for the case of non-exchangeable ratings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The confidence intervals based on the arcsine and Fisher transforms perform
 better than the basic, untransformed interval.
 It is unclear which one of these intervals to prefer, but it barely matters
 when the sample size is sufficiently large.
 It might be possible to improve all of these intervals.
 Small-sample corrections to the variance appears feasible, with potential
 openings in the application of the delta rule and in the calculation of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 of Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "lem:limit lemma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 We have used the arcsine and Fisher transforms to improve approximate normality
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{d}$
\end_inset

, but this choice is semi-arbitrary.
 Better variance-stabilizing transformations might be found by inspecting
 the formula for the variances of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{d}$
\end_inset

 in Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:The-asymptotic-variances"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The confidence intervals used in the simulation are only known to be first-orde
r accurate.
 To make second-order accurate confidence intervals, it would be possible
 to use the explicit formula for the variances to construct studentized
 confidence intervals, i.e., bootstrap-
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 intervals 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Efron1987-ov"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which are second-order accurate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
None of these approaches are guaranteed to help when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is small, especially when dealing with categorical data, as the sampling
 distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{d}$
\end_inset

 are discrete and highly irregular.
 For example, consider the sample distribution of the Perreault–Leigh model
 (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Simulation-of-confidence-k2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) when 
\begin_inset Formula $n=20$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R=20$
\end_inset

, displayed in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:irregular"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 (We omit a dominating spike at 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.) As there are 
\begin_inset Formula $C=5<\infty$
\end_inset

 categories, there is a finite number of possible values for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{d}$
\end_inset

 to take, which is strongly reflected in the plots, especially for the nominal
 weight.
 
\end_layout

