\begin_layout Subsection*
Agreement vs disagreement 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Agreement-vs-disagreement"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Agreement weighting functions are frequently standardized to guarantee that
 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x_{1},x_{2})\geq0$
\end_inset

, e.g., 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x_{1},x_{2})=1-|x_{1}-x_{2}|/\max(|x_{1}-x_{2}|)$
\end_inset

 for the absolute value weights.
 The standardization is not necessary, as they do not change the value of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{d}$
\end_inset

 when it is possible (i.e., when 
\begin_inset Formula $\max(|x_{1}-x_{2}|)<\infty$
\end_inset

), and is undefined otherwise.
 We choose not use this operation, as it does not change the value of the
 agreement coefficients in this paper, and is impossible to do when the
 range of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2}$
\end_inset

 is unbounded.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Proof of equivalence between 
\begin_inset Formula $V(d_{p})(\boldsymbol{x}_{1},\boldsymbol{x}_{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $||\boldsymbol{x}_{1}-\boldsymbol{x}_{2}||$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Proof-of-equivalence"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We will show that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(d_{p})[\boldsymbol{x}_{1},\boldsymbol{x}_{2}]=\frac{1}{2}||\boldsymbol{x}_{1}-\boldsymbol{x}_{2}||_{p},\quad V(d_{p}^{p})[\boldsymbol{x}_{1},\boldsymbol{x}_{2}]=\frac{1}{2^{p}}||\boldsymbol{x}_{1}-\boldsymbol{x}_{2}||_{p}^{p}.
\]

\end_inset

First, consider the case when 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Using translation invariance and homogeneity of the norm,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
 &  & ||x_{1}-\mu||_{p}+||x_{2}-\mu||_{p},\\
 & = & ||x_{1}-\frac{x_{1}+x_{2}}{2}-\mu+\frac{x_{1}+x_{2}}{2}||_{p}+||x_{2}-\frac{x_{1}+x_{2}}{2}-\mu+\frac{x_{1}+x_{2}}{2}||_{p},\\
 & = & ||\frac{x_{1}-x_{2}}{2}-\nu||_{p}+||-\frac{x_{1}-x_{2}}{2}-\nu||_{p},\\
 & = & ||a-\nu||_{p}+||a+\nu||_{p},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\frac{x_{1}-x_{2}}{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\mu-\frac{x_{1}+x_{2}}{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\argmin_{\nu}||a+\nu||_{p}+||a-\nu||_{p}=0,\quad\text{for all }a
\]

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\frac{x_{1}+x_{2}}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
By the Minkowski inequality,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2^{p}||a||^{p}=||a+\nu+a-\nu||^{p}\leq(||a-\nu||+||a+\nu||)^{p}.
\]

\end_inset

This is an equality if 
\begin_inset Formula $||a-\nu||=||a+\nu||=||a||$
\end_inset

, i.e., when 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=0,$
\end_inset

 as the left side equals 
\begin_inset Formula $(||a-\mu||+||a+\mu||)^{p}=2^{p}||a||^{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Now it's easy to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $V(d_{p})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V(d_{p}^{p})$
\end_inset

 have the claimed form; just substitute the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\frac{x_{1}+x_{2}}{2}$
\end_inset

 into the formula for the Fréchet variance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}(||x_{1}-\mu||_{p}+||x_{2}-\mu||_{p})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
When 
\begin_inset Formula $0<p<1$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\mapsto||x_{1}-\mu||_{p}+||x_{2}-\mu||_{p}$
\end_inset

 is stepwise concave on 
\begin_inset Formula $[-\infty,x_{1}]$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $[x_{1},x_{2}]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $[x_{2},\infty)$
\end_inset

, hence its minimum is either 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2}$
\end_inset

, or both.
 It's clear that both 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $||x_{1}-x_{2}||_{p}$
\end_inset

, hence both are Fréchet means.
 The case 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

 is obvious and omitted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
True values in the normal simulation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:true values"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We give a brief explanation why the true values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{d}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $0.8$
\end_inset

 for the quadratic weights and 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\sqrt{0.2}$
\end_inset

 for the absolute value weights.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First notice that, since the marginals of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j_{2}}$
\end_inset

 are equal for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{1},j_{2}$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{d}=\pi_{d}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, we can ignore the number of raters, since the pairwise distribution
 do not depend on them.
 Then, from standard theory about the multivariate and folded normal, we
 find that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E(|X_{j_{1}}-X_{j_{2}}|)=2\sqrt{\frac{1-\rho}{\pi}},\quad E(|X_{j_{1}}-X_{j_{2}}|^{2})=2(1-\rho).
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X'_{j_{1}}$
\end_inset

be a copy of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j_{1}}$
\end_inset

 that is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $E(|X'_{j_{1}}-X_{j_{2}}|)=2/\sqrt{\pi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E(|X'_{j_{1}}-X_{j_{2}}|^{2})=2$
\end_inset

.
 Now rewrite the kappas using disagreement instead of agreement.
 Use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{wa}-p_{fa})/(1-p_{fa})=1-d_{wa}/d_{fa}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{wa}=1-E(w(X_{j_{1}},X_{j_{2}}))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{fa}=1-E(w(X'_{j_{1}},X_{j_{2}}))$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $X'_{j_{1}}$
\end_inset

is a copy of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j_{1}}$
\end_inset

 that is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{d}=\pi_{d}=1-E(|X_{j_{1}}-X_{j_{2}}|)/E(|X'_{j_{1}}-X_{j_{2}}|^{2})=1-\sqrt{1-\rho}$
\end_inset

 for the absolute value weights and 
\begin_inset Formula $1-E(|X_{j_{1}}-X_{j_{2}}|^{2})/E(|X'_{j_{1}}-X_{j_{2}}|^{2})=\rho$
\end_inset

 for the quadratic weights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Variance-of--statistics"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}^{2}$
\end_inset

 be two 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 observations with symmetric kernel functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Define
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sigma_{cc}^{2} & = & \Cov(E[\psi_{1}(X_{1},\ldots,X_{k_{1}})\mid X_{1},\ldots,X_{c})],E[\psi_{2}(X_{1},\ldots,X_{k_{2}})\mid X_{1},\ldots,X_{c})]).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
The exact covariance of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Cov(U_{1}^{n},U_{2}^{n})=\binom{n}{k_{1}}^{-1}\sum_{c=1}^{k_{1}}\binom{k_{2}}{c}\binom{n-k_{2}}{k_{1}-c}\sigma_{cc}^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{2}$
\end_inset

 are fixed, its asymptotic variance is 
\begin_inset Formula $n\Cov(U_{1}^{n},U_{2}^{n})\to k_{1}k_{2}\sigma_{11}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Theorem 2, p. 17"
key "Lee2019-xm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Theorem 2, p. 76"
key "Lee2019-xm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Expanding the definitions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Expanding-the-definitions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is sketch of how we could expand the definitions in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Pairwise-kappa-like-statistics"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to encompass more complicated scenarios.
 We restrict ourselves to 
\begin_inset Formula $g=2$
\end_inset

, but the analysis can be expanded to arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that any finite number of raters 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is possible, the raters are not exchangeable, and that not every item is
 rated by every rater.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 denote a rating, 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 be a raters, and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be the items rated.
 Suppose we sample pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(X_{1},J_{1},I_{1}),(X_{2},J_{2},I_{2})$
\end_inset

 independently from the same distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Then we may define
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
D_{d} & = & E[d(X_{1},X_{2})\mid I_{1}=I_{2},J_{1}\neq J_{2}],\label{eq:new_definitions}\\
C_{d} & = & E[d(X_{1},X_{2})\mid J_{1}\neq J_{2}],\nonumber \\
F_{d} & = & E[d(X_{1},X_{2})].\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

These quantities have natural sample analogues, e.g., 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{D}_{d}=N^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j_{1}\neq j_{2}}d(x_{ij_{1}},x_{ij_{2}}),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the total number of paired observations and the rater indices run over
 the raters who observed at the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th observation 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Population and sample definitions of Cohen's kappa and Fleiss' kappa follow
 as laid out in the main text, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{d}=1-D_{d}/C_{d}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Krippendorff's alpha
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now suppose that the ratings can take on only a finite number 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 distinct values.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $o_{ck}$
\end_inset

 as the number of times a pair of raters has classified an item into 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
o_{ck}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j_{1}\neq j_{2}}1[x_{ij_{1}}=c,x_{ij_{2}}=k].
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\sum_{c,k}o_{ck}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}_{d}=N^{-1}\sum_{c,k}o_{ck}d(c,k).$
\end_inset

 Moreover, define 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{c}$
\end_inset

 as the number of items classified as 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{c}=\sum_{k}o_{ck}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{c}n_{c}=N$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{c,k}n_{c}n_{k}d(c,k)=N^{2}\hat{F}_{d}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:krippendorfff"

\end_inset

Using the definitions above, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}_{d}=\hat{\pi}_{d}+\frac{1}{N}(1-\hat{\pi}_{d})$
\end_inset

.
 Since there are 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2Rn$
\end_inset

 rating pairs in the rectangular setup used in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Pairwise-kappa-like-statistics"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}_{w}=\hat{\pi}_{w}+\frac{1}{2Rn}(1-\hat{\pi}_{w})$
\end_inset

 in that case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}_{w}$
\end_inset

 can be found on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p .235"
key "Krippendorff2018-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\alpha}_{w}=1-(N-1)\frac{\sum_{c\neq k}o_{ck}d(c,k)}{\sum_{c\neq k}n_{c}n_{k}d(c,k)}.
\]

\end_inset

From the definitions above, and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $d(c,k)=0$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $c=k$
\end_inset

, we find that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{c\neq k}o_{ck}d(c,k)=\sum_{c,k}o_{ck}d(c,k)=N\hat{D}_{d}.
\]

\end_inset

In the same way,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{c\neq k}n_{c}n_{k}d(c,k)=\sum_{c,k}n_{c}n_{k}d(c,k)=N^{2}\hat{F}_{d}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\alpha}_{d}=1-\frac{(N-1)}{N}\frac{\hat{D}_{d}}{\hat{F}_{d}}=1-\frac{\hat{D}_{d}}{\hat{F}_{d}}+\frac{1}{N}\frac{\hat{D}_{d}}{\hat{F}_{d}},
\]

\end_inset

and using that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{d}=1-\frac{\hat{D}_{d}}{\hat{F}_{d}}$
\end_inset

, we're done.
\end_layout

